f inclusion. By theorizing feeling otherwise as an antisocial affect, form of dissent, and mode of care, Yao suggests that unfeeling can serve as a contemporary political strategy for people of color to survive in the face of continuing racism and white fragility.Duke University Press Scholars of Color First Book Award recipient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAffect (Psychology) in literature. 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAsians in literature. 0aEmotions in literature. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aRace in literature. 0aSentimentalism in literature. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology) in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh  a2022 Arthur Miller First Book Prize honorable mention.  aBritish Association of American Studies book awards.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022107?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022107423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022107/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075418-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_E